---
applyTo: '**/*.js'
---
# Testing Instructions

TLDR: Every behavioral change gets tests (happy + at least one failure path). Prefer integration (route → policy → service) over shallow unit mocks. Never hit real external services.

## Scope & Priorities
1. Integration: Use Supertest (or equivalent) against the running Sails app.
2. Service logic: Unit test only if complex branching or pure computation.
3. Regression: Reproduce bug with a failing test before fixing.
4. Contracts: Assert HTTP status, payload shape, and critical fields (not every field unless required by contract).

## Directory Layout (convention)
test/
  integration/<domain>/<entity>.spec.js
  unit/<domain>/<service>.spec.js

## Required Cases (per new/changed endpoint)
- Happy path (200/201/204).
- Validation failure (400) via policy (e.g., missing required field).
- Auth or permission rejection (401 or 403) when applicable.
- Edge pagination (limit > max ⇒ clamped / rejected as per policy) if paginated.
- Batch partial (207) when introducing partial success logic.

## Error Field Backward Compatibility
Legacy endpoints that historically returned `error_code` must still expose it until versioned. Add/update a test asserting presence of legacy field plus (optionally) new `errorCode` if migration approved.

## Patterns
Arrange → Act → Assert; one logical assertion group per test. Use descriptive `it("should <do thing>")` messages.

## Test Data
- Prefer factory helpers / builders over hard-coded sprawling fixtures.
- Clean up created DB entities (or use isolated database / transaction rollback if configured).

## Stubbing & External IO
- Stub outbound HTTP / message bus / file system. No real network calls.
- Time-based logic: inject clock or use small fake timers (avoid large waits > 200ms).

## Assertions
- Status code is correct (no 200 for create ⇒ expect 201, etc.).
- Success shape: `{ status, message, data }` (if body present).
- Error shape: includes legacy field(s) as required.
- No stack traces or internal driver errors in body.

## Prohibited / Red Flags
- Sleeping (`setTimeout`) to “wait” for async—poll or inject hooks.
- Depending on test execution order.
- Large random data generators without seeding (flaky).
- Snapshot testing of large JSON that frequently changes (high maintenance).

## Performance in Tests
- Keep each test < 500ms; investigate slower ones (DB indices? redundant setup?).
- Parallelize independent describe blocks only if isolation guaranteed.

## When to Ask Before Writing Tests
- Unclear expected failure status (400 vs 422 vs 409).
- Mixed legacy/new error fields ambiguity.
- Missing policy yet validation required.
- Required seed data / reference data unspecified.

## Developer Defense Link
In PR body: list new/changed tests + rationale for any test you deliberately skipped (with `// JUSTIFICATION:` inside test file if rule exception).

Keep tests minimal, deterministic, and contract-focused.
